Perspectives for Sino-American Relations in 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of China-U.S. relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
Exactly a year ago, U.S. President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grandiose "state visit plus" from Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-China campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
In addition, the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty in the financial markets, growth is slowing in China and Europe, and in America, higher interest rates are beginning to take effect.
The uncertainty regarding the future development of nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What, then, are the prospects for U.S.-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard will be reached by March.
An agreement on lowering tariffs is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one by one, it could take a year.
Should Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing themselves to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to do the same, a faster result could be in sight.
This, however, would run counter to the Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Nevertheless, a reform is something different from the way contractual agreements could be interpreted in practice, even if there were no specific provisions on technology transfer at all.
Protection of intellectual property, however, is extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
Enforcement or judicial action against violations of intellectual property rights, however, remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration courts based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration process based in China.
In order to strengthen international credibility, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel.
No one has trust in Chinese commercial courts.
To meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent commercial and civil chambers within its judicial system, even if the penal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies within the framework of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will be difficult to resolve.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain level of state support to their domestic technology industries, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, the compliance would be difficult to assess.
I am not confident that there will be a negotiation result in this area.
Perhaps America simply has to outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not exclude the possibility that China offers tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
Thus, China could decide over time to take the drastic step of agreeing to tariff-free trade not only with the United States, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would have an almost irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to counter the trend towards protectionism.
In the course of such a shift, China could invite the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, in order to surpass the United States (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably nimble when it detects a political opening and market liberalization.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the United States, China is likely to be striving in 2019 in its general foreign and security policy to reduce conflicts in its relations with other countries.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a clear reduction in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also aims to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea through accelerated negotiations on a "Code of Conduct."
Moreover, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, in light of the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the USA continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the USA in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the USA more vigorously emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Throughout all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project "Belt and Road Initiative."
In recent months, however, the initiative has caused less political uproar in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financiability of the Belt and Road Initiative.
In 2019, therefore, triumphal news about the New Silk Road could be heard less frequently.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlight new institutions of international political action.
It will probably continue to appear as a new advocate of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More prudent representatives of the foreign policy establishment in China believe it is better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially if the USA consistently shows contempt for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the USA and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will likely use the year 2019 to form a well-founded judgment about the future of US policy: The consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already come to the conclusion that America's stance toward China has undergone profound changes, they are still uncertain about exactly what form this change will take and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
